{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609786"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:50:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:50:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16122"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16122"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.63,0,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8813"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49406"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5119"},{"type":"tags","id":"8681"},{"type":"tags","id":"10135"},{"type":"tags","id":"10552"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21028"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21031"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring male embryonic development, androgens play crucial roles in sexual differentiation. Different androgen-dependent processes require either testosterone or its derivative dihydrotestosterone (DHT).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops under the influence of dihydrotestosterone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epididymis","Seminal vesicles","External genitalia","Vas deferens","Prostate gland"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring male sexual differentiation, \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal genitalia\u003C/strong\u003E including the penis and scrotum develop from the genital tubercle and labioscrotal swellings under the influence of DHT. This hormone is produced from testosterone by the enzyme 5-alpha reductase in target tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Wolffian duct derivatives including the \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymis\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Evas deferens\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eseminal vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E develop in response to testosterone, not DHT. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate gland\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the urogenital sinus under the influence of DHT, but is considered an internal structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis distinction between testosterone and DHT-dependent structures is clinically relevant in conditions such as 5-alpha reductase deficiency, where affected individuals have normal internal male structures but ambiguous external genitalia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dihydrotestosterone (DHT) is essential for external male genital development including the penis and scrotum.","DHT is produced from testosterone by the enzyme 5-alpha reductase in target tissues.","The Wolffian duct structures (epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles) develop in response to testosterone, not DHT."],"references":["Hutson JM, Li R, Southwell BR, Petersen BL, Thorup J, Cortes D. Germ cell development in the postnatal testis: the key to prevent malignancy in cryptorchidism? Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2013 Jan 3;3:176. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2012.00176. PMID: 23316184; PMCID: PMC3539691","P A A, Arbor TC, Krishan K. Embryology, Sexual Development. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557601/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49406"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16122"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49406"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T20:29:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T20:30:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8813"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63977"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4934"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Reproductive System (Male)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"20